Architecture plan for issues #3-#10

Scope
- Build a dependency-light static browser clock that renders local time as
  HH:MM:SS, updates every wall-clock second, and can be opened directly or
  served by a simple static server.
- Keep the implementation intentionally small: plain HTML, CSS, and JavaScript
  first; introduce test tooling only for the unit and browser tests.

Module structure and file organization
- index.html
  - Browser entry point.
  - Contains a single main landmark with an empty div#clock.
  - Links to styles.css and clock.js.
- styles.css
  - Full-viewport document reset.
  - Centered main/clock layout.
  - Responsive monospace clock typography using clamp() and tabular digits.
- clock.js
  - Exports or exposes formatTime(date), a pure Date -> "HH:MM:SS" formatter.
  - Owns DOM startup on DOMContentLoaded.
  - Renders #clock immediately, then schedules the next tick aligned to the
    next wall-clock second before continuing at 1000ms intervals.
- tests/unit
  - Unit coverage for formatTime: midnight, noon, and single-digit padding.
  - Prefer node --test if clock.js is made importable without browser globals;
    otherwise use a tiny test.html runner.
- tests/e2e
  - Playwright spec serving the static directory and validating that #clock
    matches the HH:MM:SS pattern and changes after about 1.2 seconds.
- README.md
  - Final polish target for a short project description, run/test commands,
    and screenshot or screenshot placeholder as required by issue #10.

Shared types and contracts
- The only shared contract is formatTime(date): string.
- formatTime must be deterministic for a provided Date and must not read the
  DOM, timers, or current time internally.
- DOM code should treat #clock as required page structure and fail visibly in
  tests if the element is missing.

Dependencies between issues
- #3 scaffolds the HTML shell and establishes the public DOM target.
- #4 depends on #3 because styles target the page shell and #clock element.
- #5 depends on #4 because typography builds on the centered layout.
- #6 depends on #3 because clock.js is linked from the shell, but stays pure
  enough for independent unit testing.
- #7 depends on #6 and #3 because it combines formatTime with the DOM target
  and timer behavior.
- #8 depends on #6 because it validates the pure formatter contract.
- #9 depends on #7 because the browser test needs the live render/tick loop.
- #10 depends on #4, #5, #7, #8, and #9 because polish should verify layout,
  responsiveness, browser behavior, console cleanliness, and documentation.

Key design decisions
- Use plain static assets. No framework or bundler is needed for this app.
- Keep clock.js testable by separating pure formatting from DOM/timer startup.
- Prefer an ES module script if node --test is selected; otherwise keep a
  browser-global function plus a test.html harness to preserve direct-open use.
- Align the first delayed update to the next second boundary with
  1000 - new Date().getMilliseconds(), then use setInterval(1000) after that.
- Use system monospace fonts and font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums so the
  displayed width remains stable as seconds change.
- Keep CSS neutral and restrained: full-viewport centering, no decorative
  dependencies, no layout shift from dynamic clock text.
